2196B - Another Problem about Beautiful Pairs
Consider the following solution:
For each $$$i$$$, we will check all possible candidates $$$j$$$ that can form beautiful pairs. To do this, we will iterate through such $$$j = i + k \cdot a_{i}$$$, where $$$k  \gt  0$$$.
This solution works slowly for small $$$a_{i}$$$. Let's try to speed it up using square root decomposition. We will introduce a parameter $$$B$$$ and will iterate through candidates for $$$i$$$ in different ways depending on whether $$$a_{i}  \lt  B$$$ or $$$a_{i} \ge B$$$:
If $$$a_{i} \ge B$$$, we will iterate through candidates in both directions from $$$i$$$ (not just forward), meaning for each such $$$i$$$, the set of candidates will be $$$i + k \cdot a_{i}$$$, where $$$k$$$ is any integer;
If $$$a_{i}  \lt  B$$$, we will also iterate through candidates only forward, but we will introduce an additional restriction on $$$k$$$, namely $$$k  \lt  B$$$.
Let's estimate the maximum possible number of candidates for these two cases:
In the first case, for all such $$$i$$$ where $$$a_{i} \ge B$$$, it is $$$\frac{n}{B}$$$, since we move in steps of $$$B$$$;
In the second case, it is clear that there are no more than $$$B$$$ candidates, as we have introduced such a restriction ourselves.
If we choose $$$B = \lceil\sqrt{n}\rceil$$$, then the number of candidates for each case is no more than $$$\lceil\sqrt{n}\rceil$$$, so the entire algorithm solves the problem in $$$O(n\sqrt{n})$$$.
Let's think about why such an algorithm will be correct. Consider the cases of a beautiful pair $$$(i, j)$$$, depending on the values of $$$a_{i}$$$ and $$$a_{j}$$$:
If $$$a_{i}  \lt  B$$$ and $$$a_{j}  \lt  B$$$, then the pair will be counted when we iterate through candidates for $$$i$$$;
If $$$a_{i} \ge B$$$ and $$$a_{j}  \lt  B$$$, then the pair will be counted when we iterate through candidates for $$$j$$$;
If $$$a_{i}  \lt  B$$$ and $$$a_{j} \ge B$$$, then the pair will be counted when we iterate through candidates for $$$j$$$;
Note that there is no case where $$$a_{i} \ge B$$$ and $$$a_{j} \ge B$$$, since we chose $$$B = \lceil\sqrt{n}\rceil$$$, which means that in such a pair $$$a_{i} \cdot a_{j} \ge n$$$, and the maximum value of $$$j - i = n - 1$$$.
Therefore, our algorithm is correct
